<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-685-307  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 685 307.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 27 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Harris receives $11 million Army contract. (Harris Corp.andO;Government Electronic Systems Division, tactical communicationssystems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Harris Corp. Government Support Systems Div. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    HRS.andO;Topic:     United States. ArmyDefense ContractsCommunications EquipmentMobile Radio Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HARRIS RECEIVES $11 MILLION ARMY CONTRACT 11/27/90 MELBOURNE, FLORIDA,U.S.A., 1990 NOV 27 (NB) -- Harris Corporation has announced that itsGovernment Electronic Systems Division (GESD) has been awarded an $11 millioncontract by the U.S.andP;  Army to produce portable tactical communicationssystems.andP;  Harris also stated that the Army may also select options increasingthe contract value to $59 million.andM;The two-year contract was awarded by the U.S.andP;  Army's Communications-Electronics Command at Fort Monmouth, N.J.andP;  Under the contract, Harris GESDwill integrate, test, and deliver the Digital Group Multiplexer Antenna MastProgram (DAMP) systems.andP;  The systems will be used in forward communicationsoutposts and include an antenna positioner and a graphite mast adjustablefrom three to 30 meters in height.andP;  The contract stipulates that Harris willdeliver 200 mast assemblies and 75 transport pallet assemblies and the Armyhas the option of ordering up to 1,800 additional masts and 900 transportassemblies.andM;As prime contractor, Harris will integrate the DAMP systems and design andbuild the pallet assemblies, which support and protect the ancillaryequipment masts, and positioners while they are being stowed and transported.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19901126/Press Contact: Jim Burke,Harris Corporation, 407-727-9126)</TEXT></DOC>